Subject to these, the commission appointed to execute the work, which consisted (besides Tribonian, who superintended it throughout) of sixteen per- sons, possessed the same powers of omission, alteration, and modifi- oetion as had been exercised by the compilers of the Code. They were instructed not to limit themselves to the five leading jurists who occupy so prominent a position in the ‘law of Citations,' but to select whatever was valuable in the works of all the ‘ iuris auctores.' The only exception to this was their admission of Arcadius Charisius and Hermogenian, both of whom lived after Modestinus, and accordingly had not possessed the ius respondendi. The total number of jurists upon whom they drew for their materials was thirty-nine.
